“Now I’ll provide a quick demo of the CFG_VW_CONTROL Streamlit application in the development environment.
I’ll share my screen.
Currently I’m in the Snowflake non-production environment.
From the home page, I’ll navigate to Projects, and under Projects I’ll select Streamlit Apps.
Here we can see the list of available Streamlit applications developed by the team.
I’ll open the CFG_VW_CONTROL App.
Once the application opens, the app allows users to search records either by Program Name or by View Name.
This helps users quickly identify the exact view configuration record they want to update.
For this demo, I’ll search using the Program Name.
I’ll enter the Program Name as ‘Focus Survey’ and click ‘Search for Program’.
Now the application returns all records related to the Focus Survey program.
Here we can see multiple views such as:


VW_COMBINED_SURVEY


VW_METRIC_RESPONSE


VW_METRIC_TARGET
and other related views.


For this demo, I’ll select the view called VW_METRIC_TARGET_RPD.
Here we can see the current configuration values stored in the CFG_VW_CONTROL table.
The table includes columns such as:


PROGRAM_NAME


VIEW_NAME


MIN_DISPLAY_DATE


MAX_DISPLAY_DATE


USER_STORY


COMMENTS


UPDATE_DATE


UPDATE_USER


These values control how data flows through the reporting views based on configured display date ranges.
Currently, the MAX_DISPLAY_DATE is set to 2025-12-01.
For this demonstration, I’ll update the MAX_DISPLAY_DATE value to 2030-12-31.
I’ll select the date and make the update.
Now I’ll click the Update button.
At this point, the application processes only the modified row instead of updating the full dataset.
The UPDATE_DATE column is automatically populated using the current Snowflake system timestamp.
The UPDATE_USER column is also automatically populated using the logged-in Streamlit user session information.
This removes manual audit handling and improves update consistency.
Now we can see the success message confirming that the record was updated successfully.
If we refresh or search again, we can verify that the updated MAX_DISPLAY_DATE value is now saved in Snowflake.
This demonstrates how the Streamlit enhancement simplified backend table maintenance, improved audit tracking, and optimized the update process.”
“One enhancement I implemented was automating the UPDATE_DATE audit column.
Previously, users could manually edit this value, which could lead to inconsistencies.
To improve audit reliability, I removed UPDATE_DATE from editable fields and automatically assigned the latest system timestamp using Snowflake’s current_timestamp() function.
This ensures every update reflects the actual system update time automatically.”
